    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4092246351" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4092246351" />
    <a title="Debbie Zapata" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22110057-debbie-zapata"><img alt="Debbie Zapata" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451631863p2/22110057.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4092246351?book_show_action=true">Jul 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debbie Zapata" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debbie Zapata" href="/user/show/22110057-debbie-zapata">Debbie Zapata</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780156656009" href="/book/show/1168284.Night_and_Day">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22110057-debbie-zapata?shelf=21print">21print</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4092246351" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2122788949890673153">Jul 12 ~~ Review asap. Torn between three and four stars so might change my mind after I think on it a bit.<br/><br/>Jul 14 ~~ Woolf&apos;s second published novel, this 1920 book was both fascinating and puzzling for me. I was interested in the inside view of a certain level of British society, and at the same time I kept wondering how hard it could possibly be for these characters to figure out how they felt about each other. I was reminded many times of a dear friend of mine from back in my younger days. Onc</span>
  <span id="freeText2122788949890673153" style="display:none">Jul 12 ~~ Review asap. Torn between three and four stars so might change my mind after I think on it a bit.<br /><br />Jul 14 ~~ Woolf's second published novel, this 1920 book was both fascinating and puzzling for me. I was interested in the inside view of a certain level of British society, and at the same time I kept wondering how hard it could possibly be for these characters to figure out how they felt about each other. I was reminded many times of a dear friend of mine from back in my younger days. Once when we were discussing Life he told me "You think too much. You need to just live." This was not a romantic friend, more of an older brother/uncle type of relationship. And he was right. So at dozens of points throughout this book, I channeled my friend Luis to tell Katharine Hilbery and the people around her the same thing. <br /><br />I became very well acquainted with the characters of this book. Woolf brings them to life, even if the book does seem to crawl along and I often wanted to smack everyone upside the head to get them moving a little faster. <br /><br />I loved this line about Katharine's mother(and my book does indeed say in, not on, but I am not at all sure that is correct since there were a few obvious typos in other places). Anyway, this was a perfect description of Mother:<br /><b>She was beautifully adapted for life in another planet.</b><br /><br />She seemed so abstract, so very much in her own little world, that at the end I was surprised at how she handled the 'crisis'. She turned out to be a very cool lady, and not nearly as spaced out as she seemed.<br /><br />So the basic plot here is the classic idea of a group of people dealing with their feelings for each other. He loves, she loves, he loves, she doesn't love....or does she? And then another young person arrives on scene and she loves too. But who loves who and how each person reacts to the inner awareness of their own emotions and what fears that awareness produces is what drives the story. Do they ever pair off properly? And who is it that does not become part of a romantic pair after all? <br /><br />It can feel like a slow motion book. But the ending was so worth the effort! I adored the last few chapters, I even cried. Now I admit that I do tend to cry easily with books, but the way Woolf wrapped everything up was simply so splendid I couldn't help myself. <br /><br />And yes, I bumped up from three to four stars after all. <br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="2122788949890673153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


